This way you don&#39;t have two separate if blocks.

When You add an if it checks all of the conditions until you get out of it and continue your code or have an else.&lt;br /&gt;
So, it means when it checks the first if it checks the second if to.&lt;br /&gt;
So use elif for the second if.

All you need to do is change the second if statement to an elif statement (elif stands for else if). In your code, what is happening is that the first statement is being considered as one if section and the second if - else section is being checked again. So, in a way, there are two if/if - else sections. Hence, the 2 outputs.  By changing the second if to elif, you&#39;ll be reducing the two if/if - else sections to just one and there will be only one output. Try this code:

    var1 = 50
    var2 = input(&quot;choose a number = &quot;)
    if int(var2)&gt;var1:
        print(&quot;greater&quot;)
    elif int(var2)==var1:
        print(&quot;equal&quot;)
    else:
        print(&quot;lesser&quot;)

